org.kiji.schema
Interface KijiPager

All Superinterfaces:
Closeable, Iterator<KijiRowData>
All Known Implementing Classes:
HBaseMapFamilyPager, HBaseVersionPager
@ApiAudience.Public
@ApiStability.Experimental
@Inheritance.Sealed
public interface KijiPager
extends Iterator<KijiRowData>, Closeable

Retrieves pages of values from a column in a Kiji table.

KijiPager is useful when requesting a large number of values from a column. The page size is an upper limit to the number of cells retrieved from the region servers at a time, to bound the amount of memory consumed on the client machine.

To enable paging on a column, use KijiDataRequestBuilder.ColumnsDef.withPageSize(int) when building a KijiDataRequest. For example, using a group type column "info:name", you may request a maximum of 2 versions per page, with a maximum of 5 versions per qualifier as follows: 

     final KijiDataRequest dataRequest = KijiDataRequest.builder()
         .addColumnsDef(ColumnsDef.create()
             .withMaxVersions(5)  // at most 5 versions per column qualifier
             .withPageSize(2)     // at most 2 cells per page
             .add("info", "name"))
         .build();

To get a KijiPager, call KijiRowData.getPager(java.lang.String) or KijiRowData.getPager(String, String) on a KijiRowData constructed with paging enabled: 

     final KijiTableReader reader = ...
     final EntityId entityId = ...
     final KijiRowData row = reader.get(entityId, dataRequest);
     final KijiPager pager = row.getPager("info", "name");
     try  {
       while(pager.hasNext()) {
         final KijiRowData page = pager.next();
         // Use: page.getValues("info", "name")
         // ...
       }
     } finally {
       // Always close pagers:
       pager.close();
     }

Notes:
  • The page size in an upper bound to the number of cells retrieved in a page. Concretely, a page of cells returned by next() or next(int) may contain less cells than the page size, even if there are more pages coming. In particular, there may be empty pages even when more pages follow. Use Iterator.hasNext() to determine if more pages follow.
  • When paging over a map-type family, retrieved pages only contain the qualifiers in the family, and no cell content. You may retrieve the cell content with a get request with the qualifiers from the pager. If you need to retrieve many versions for all these qualifier, you may combine the map-family pager with per-qualifier pagers.

If you don't need access to individual pages, you may use the following iterator/iterable helpers:

  • ColumnVersionIterator iterates through the versions in a given column.
  • MapFamilyQualifierIterator iterates through the qualifiers in a map-type family.
  • MapFamilyVersionIterator iterates through the versions in all columns from a map-type family.

See Also:
ColumnVersionIterator, MapFamilyQualifierIterator, MapFamilyVersionIterator

KijiRowData next()
Fetches the next page of cells from the Kiji table using the configured page size.
  • The page size is an upper bound to the number of cells retrieved from the table.
  • The page may contain fewer cells than the specified page size. In particular, the page can sometimes be empty, even though more pages follow.
    • Use Iterator.hasNext() to determine if more pages follow.

next

KijiRowData next(int pageSize)
Fetches the next page of cells from the Kiji table using the specified page size.
  • The page size is an upper bound to the number of cells retrieved from the table.
  • The page may contain less cells than the specified page size. In particular, the page can sometimes be empty, even though more pages follow.
    • Use Iterator.hasNext() to determine if more pages follow.

Parameters:
pageSize - The maximum number of cells to retrieve for this page.
Returns:
the next page of data as a KijiRowData. Never null, but potentially empty.
